  "opinion": "As a 55-year-old self-employed cleaner from Kansas City, I spend about an hour a day on social media, mostly to unwind after work or during breaks, and I've seen my fair share of fake content pop up. Being naturally curious, thanks to my high openness, I often dig deeper into things that catch my eye, but I've learned to be cautious because my low conscientiousness means I'm not always the most organized or thorough in checking facts. Living in a relationship without kids, I value my time and don't want to waste it on nonsense. From my perspective, dealing with fake content starts with trusting your gut—if something seems too good or too shocking to be true, it probably is. I remember seeing a post about a miracle cure that went viral, and my curiosity led me to look it up; turns out it was debunked by health experts. As a Muslim, I believe in honesty and integrity, which guides me to avoid spreading lies. I think social media platforms should step up more, maybe by flagging suspicious posts or providing easy ways to report them, but ultimately, it's on us users to be smart. I don't get too worked up about it, thanks to my moderate neuroticism, but I do feel a responsibility to not contribute to the problem. In my daily life, cycling and painting help me stay grounded, and I apply that same mindfulness online—taking a moment to pause before sharing. It's not about being perfect, but about being aware and making small, thoughtful choices to keep our online spaces a bit cleaner, just like I do in my job.",
